def barchar_group(df,x_var,groupby_var,size,name):
    """creates a barchar that represents aggregation results"""
    
    df_agg = df.loc[:, [x_var, groupby_var]].groupby(groupby_var)
    vals = [df[x_var].values.tolist() for i, df in df_agg]

    # Drawb
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,9), dpi= 80)
    colors = [plt.cm.Spectral(i/float(len(vals)-1)) for i in range(len(vals))]
    n, bins, patches = plt.hist(vals, df[x_var].unique().__len__(), stacked=False, density=False, color=colors[:len(vals)])

    # Decoration
    plt.legend({group:col for group, col in zip(np.unique(df[groupby_var]).tolist(), colors[:len(vals)])})
    plt.title(name, fontsize=22)
    plt.xlabel(x_var)
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    plt.ylim(0, size)
    plt.xticks(ticks=bins, labels=np.unique(df[x_var]).tolist(), rotation=90, horizontalalignment='left')
    plt.show()

def pca_conversion(vectors):
    """ PCA conversion for visualiztion"""
    pca = decomposition.PCA(n_components=3)
    pca.fit(vectors)
    vectors_vis = pca.transform(vectors)
    vectors_vis = pd.DataFrame(vectors_vis,columns = ["x","y","z"])
    return vectors_vis

Data Preparation¶

We will check out what is going inside the train and test data.

Features Description¶

  1. PassengerId - unique id for each passenger
  2. Survived - have the passenger survived or not {0=No,1=Yes}
  3. Pclass - A proxy for socio-economic status {1=Upper,2=Middle,3=Lower}
  4. Name - Name of the passenger
  5. Sex - sex type of the passenger {male, female}
  6. Age - age in years
  7. SibSp - number of spouses/siblings aboard the Titanic
  8. Parch - children/parents aboard the Titanic
  9. Ticket - ticket number
  10. Fare - Passenger fare
  11. Cabin - cabin numner
  12. Embarked - port of embarkation{C=Cherbourg, Q=Queenstown,S=Southampton}

Observaing Dataset¶

Number of notes:

  1. As seen below Ticket,Cabin,Name have complicated values. Later on we will take a look if I should engineer them or drop them.

  2. dataset containes "nan" values

  3. number of features from type object, should be converted

Correlating¶

In this part we will be checking how each feature correlates with Survival and between each other. By doing this we can understand which features are more significant and more importantly, which are not.

Correlating between all features¶

Findings:

  1. 0.41 between Parch and SibSp this fact suggests to create a feature from both of them
  2. 0.26 between Fare and Survived, which suggests that people how payed more had higher survival rate
  3. -0.55 Pclass and Fare had a negtive correlation which means that people from Pclass=1 (Upper Class) tend to pay more, this fact could suggest some feature engenniring between the two should be done
  4. -0.34 between Survived and Pclass which also suggests that passengers from higher class had higher chance to survive
  5. -0.35 between Survived and Age which suggest that younger passengers had higher chance for survival
  6. 0.54 between Sex and Survived suggets that females had higher chance for survival
  7. -0.31 suggests that the older the passengers had fewer spouses/siblings aboard the Titanic then younger once
  8. -0.37 suggests that older passengers were more likely to be from an Upper class

Correcting Age¶

More accurate way of guessing missing values in age is to use other correlated features. In our case we note correlation among Age ,SibSp ,parch ,Title and Pclass.

In [32]:
def fill_age_missing_values(df):
    age_null = list(df[df["Age"].isnull()].index)

    for index in age_null:
        temp_Pclass = df.iloc[index]["Pclass"]
        temp_SibSp = df.iloc[index]["SibSp"]
        temp_Parch = df.iloc[index]["Parch"]
        temp_Title = df.iloc[index]["Title"]
        
        age_median = df["Age"][(
            (df["Pclass"] == temp_Pclass) & 
            (df["Pclass"] == temp_Pclass) & 
            (df["SibSp"] == temp_SibSp) & 
            (df["Parch"] == temp_Parch) & 
            (df["Title"] == temp_Title)
        )].median()
        
        df["Age"].iloc[index] = age_median if (df.iloc[index]["Age"] == True) and (np.isnan(age_median) == False) else df["Age"].median()
    return df

age_groups = ['Baby',  'Child', 'Young Adult', 'Adult', 'Senior']

for dataset in combine:
    dataset.loc[(dataset['Age'] <= 2), 'Age Group'] = 0
    dataset.loc[((dataset["Age"] > 2) & (dataset['Age'] <= 10)), 'Age Group'] = 1 
    dataset.loc[((dataset["Age"] > 10) & (dataset['Age'] <= 19)), 'Age Group'] = 2
    dataset.loc[((dataset["Age"] > 19) & (dataset['Age'] <= 60)), 'Age Group'] = 3
    dataset.loc[(dataset["Age"] > 60), 'Age Group'] = 4
    
    dataset["Age"] = dataset["Age"].astype(int)
    dataset["Age Group"] = dataset["Age Group"].astype(int)

titles = ["Master", "Miss", "Mr", "Royals", "Professionals"]

for dataset in combine:
    dataset.Title = dataset.Title.replace(['Lady', 'the Countess', 'Countess', 'Don', 'Jonkheer', 'Dona', 'Sir'], 'Royals')
    dataset.Title = dataset.Title.replace(['Col', 'Dr', 'Major', 'Capt'], 'Professionals')
    dataset.Title = dataset.Title.replace(["Ms", "Mme", "Mlle", "Mrs"], 'Miss')
    dataset.Title = dataset.Title.replace(['Master', 'Rev'], 'Mas/Rev')

KNN¶

Neighbors-based classification is a type of instance-based learning or non-generalizing learning Classification is computed from a simple majority vote of the nearest neighbors of each point.

We choose the number of neighbors for optimization by using cross-validation method

In [68]:
neighbors = list(range(1,50,2))


cv_scores = [ ]
for K in neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = K)
    scores = cross_val_score(knn,x_train,y_train,cv = 10,scoring =
    "accuracy")
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())

Choosing best K("number of neighbors")

In [69]:
mse = [1-x for x in cv_scores]
optimal_k = neighbors[mse.index(min(mse))]
print("The optimal no. of neighbors is {}".format(optimal_k))

The optimal no. of neighbors is 33
In [70]:
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=optimal_k, metric='euclidean')

GMM¶

A Gaussian mixture model is a probabilistic model that assumes all the data points are generated from a mixture of a finite number of Gaussian distributions with unknown parameters. One can think of mixture models as generalizing k-means clustering to incorporate information about the covariance structure of the data as well as the centers of the latent Gaussians.

To choose the best parameters for the model we will use silhouette, and choose the best parameters according to it

In [81]:
evluate_sil = {}
n_components_range = range(2, 6)
cv_types = ['spherical', 'tied', 'diag', 'full']

# checking what are the best parameters for GMM
for cv_type in cv_types:
    
    sil = []
    for n_components in n_components_range:
        # Fit a Gaussian mixture with EM
        gmm = mixture.GaussianMixture(n_components=n_components,
                                      covariance_type=cv_type,random_state=RSEED)
        gmm.fit(x_train)
        labels = gmm.predict(x_train)
        sil.append(silhouette_score(x_train, labels, metric = 'euclidean'))

    evluate_sil[cv_type] = sil



for key in evluate_sil:
    plt.plot(n_components_range, evluate_sil[key],label=key) # plotting t, c separately 

plt.xlabel("components")
plt.ylabel("silhouette_score")
plt.legend(loc=1)
plt.show()

The choosen parameters for the GMM will be:

  • method - tied
  • number of components = 2
In [82]:
gmm = mixture.GaussianMixture(n_components=2, covariance_type=cv_type,random_state=RSEED)

x_train["Cluster"] = gmm.fit_predict(x_train)
x_test["Cluster"] = gmm.predict(x_test)

Summery¶

The addition of Clustering feature didnt effect much the evaluation score (+-1). But, in general the results of the kaggle test were effected for the worse.

Discussion¶

A little summery of what was done in the notebook

Dropping¶

The data given to us was a little corrupted, features that contained alot of missing values and alot of added value which was hidden inside the "Name" feature. Features as "PassengerID" , "Cabin" and "Ticket" were dropped.

"Name" - After extracting the title from the name, the feature shoudn't have any impact on the results

"Ticket" - Had to much missing values to try and find a signal in there

"PassengerID" - Have no effect on the result, so he was dropped

Correcting¶

Then filling process started. "Age", "Embarked" and "Fare" were completed, because they showed some correlation to "Survived". Every feature was completed under different logic.

"Age" - was completed by using correlations with different freatures

"Embarked" - most frequent value was used

"Fare" - Reduced skewness to make the distrubistion more "normal" and fill with most frequent values

Feat¶

After filling was completed, feature engineering started. We wanted to create extra value by manipulating the existing features.
The next features were created: "Fare","Title","Age Group" and Family

"Fare" - Was changed to categorical feature according to the correlations

"Family" - Categorical feature which says if the passenger has family or not, the family elemnet has strong correlaton with survivability

"Age Group" - different age groups had different chances for survival, which made sense to create a categorical feature

"Title" - People with high ranking titles had higher chances for survivability so using the title as a categorical feature made sense

By optimizimg the different models we managed to get good evaluations for the models. In general the models preformed quit well in this dataset, with "accuracy" rate around 0.78. Even by adding an extra feature (which added mainly noise) the prefomance of the models wasnt effected in a harsh way.
